metadata.name: Butterflies #16
metadata.description:
The Butterflies token is another in a series of tokens of a larger project called Kim Blood 2024. It is a total collection of digital "postage" stamps with various themes.
The tokens from this series available on fx(hash) are a combination of generatively layered pngs and a procedurally rendered barcode in a transparent image cutout.
While the individual layers are repeated with varying rarity in various rare combinations, the generated barcode is unique for each mintage.

Individual generatively layered pngs:
1. Handcrafted frame with serrations of stamps in nine color versions. These color versions are set with different rarity in a 1:1:1:1:3:3:5:5:5 ratio
2. Images created by artificial intelligence, further modified. There are a total of twelve different images with an equal chance of being minted.
So in total there are 9x12 (108) different AI image x frame combinations.
However, due to different rarities, some are repeated more often, while the rarest ones have a chance of 1:300. Because of this, the total number to be minted is set at 600, giving some chance that the rarest combinations will also be minted.
Due to the uniqueness of the generated barcode, even iterations with the same combination of generated layers are not identical, but each one is unique.
In the lower right corner, below the barcode, the rarity calculation is displayed. Specifically, it is a calculation of the chance of minting a given combination. Not a rarity among already minted iterations.

Image resolution: 1760x2250px
You can download the PNG after pressing the "s" key.

metadata.description:

metadata.name: Œ∏  #126
metadata.description:
Œ∏ (theta) is a fundamental metaphor underlying the creation of digital imagery.

‚ñí

Born from chaos/order,

Measurements or drawings of disorder/order,

Repetitive measurements/drawings,

Until it draws its own light and shadow, possessing its own time.

‚ñí

When W. J. T. Mitchell discusses the concept of "digital imagery" and references a mythological figure, Urizen, who appears in the works of William Blake. Mitchell states:

"Urizen represents measurement and division, drawing the circumference of the world and delineating the boundaries between light and darkness, serving as the sacred rational architect fundamental to the visible universe."
‚Äî " Image Science: Iconology, Visual Culture, and Media Aesthetics " Chapter 11, by W. J. T. Mitchell.

From William Blake's portrayal of Urizen, I sense a central figure in the creation of the world's myriad forms, one immersed in calculating the incalculable, measuring elusive patterns, and tracing the vortex of ever-flowing boundaries.

In my view, this represents the ongoing collaboration between humanity and computer today.

‚ñí

In mathematics, Œ∏ (theta) typically represents an angle on a plane. Through calculations involving points, lines, and angles (with the assistance of computers), we can create an almost infinite array of shapes. For me, at this level, Œ∏ has become a fundamental metaphor underlying the creation of digital imagery.

In this artwork 'Œ∏', I attempt to connect the metaphorical aspects of mythology with mathematical calculations, imagining myself as a cartographer of creation, striving to capture the fissures in image generation.

However, this also signifies that I cannot create anything outright; I am always an individual trying to master the elusive calculations. Only be continually captivated by the corporeal perception and temporal characteristics of digital imagery.

‚ñí

Taking my inspiration from impressionist and contemporary paintings, I tried to generate

I hope it will inspire you to take the time to daydream, or simply to spend a moment

metadata.name: Luminous Echos #12
metadata.description:
All outputs contain embedded blueprints for cutting a physical edition with a high powered laser out of 12 layers of archival paperboard. 

‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî-

In a realm where the very essence of creation is bound to chaos, there lies a series of masterworks, a testament to the harmonious blend of order and chaos. 

Each piece, a confluence of geometric precision and the untamed spirit of the shadow and light, invites the onlooker to traverse the boundaries of the physical and the ethereal.

The art, attracted to the strong emotions and vibrant events of the world, materializes in a cascade of circular motifs‚Äîeach a pocket of infinity, reminiscent of echoes, ancient and brimming with latent potential. The lines flow like streams of sunlight, bending and twisting in a dance choreographed by the rhythms of the universe, defying the rigid confines of two-dimensional space.

Here, in these manifestations of creativity, one might sense the influence of imagination, where thoughts and ideas cast a physical form. The colors are whispers of the cognitive realm, vibrant yet bounded by the monochrome discipline of the physical realm, creating a duality that reflects the very nature of all beings‚Äîpart of two worlds, yet fully belonging to neither.

The artist, a lightweaver of sorts, has woven a pattern of lies so majestic that they reveal a deeper truth‚Äîthe truth of beauty inherent in the mathematics of the universe, the geometry of existence, and the profound complexity hidden within the seemingly simple.

This generative series, thus named ‚ÄúLuminous Echos,‚Äù for it is a bridge between the seen and unseen, a crafted illusion that binds the soul of the observer to the eternal dance of creation and cognition‚Äîa masterful rendition regarded with a mesmerizing "Mmmmmmm."

metadata.name: PARIS #22
metadata.description:
Paris is a generative and animated piece creating shapes based on trails. 
The size, position and motion frequency of each circles are generated for each token, along with the color theme. 

Each reloading creates a different movement, as the algorithm underlying the piece is partially based on a noise.
At the end, the animation stop and the visual is created.

Created by Quentin Hocd√©, in La-Roche-Neuville (France).

metadata.name: hippieCircles #1
metadata.description:
Hippie Circles is a trip back in time to a genre of imagery I recall from my coming of age in the 1960's; psychedelic art. Bright colors and images that would blow your mind. Especially if influenced by a few tokes.

This image consists of several tessellated layers a concentric circle tile. The palette is limited to a few bright colors. I find the image remarkably simple yet visually complex at the same time. Every iteration is a new trip. Far out!

I hope you enjoy my flashback.

Please visit www.drbillkolomyjec.com
